statement:
Let

\begin{align*}b_1 = \left[ \!\!\begin{array}{c} 1 \\ -1 \end{array}\!\!\right] \quad b_2 = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 0 \end{array}\right] \quad b_3 = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 3 \\ 4 \end{array}\right]\end{align*}
Let \emph{T} denote a linear transformation of
\textbf{R}\textsuperscript{2} such that

\begin{align*}T(b_1) = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 1 \end{array}\right] \quad T(b_2) = \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \end{array}\right]\end{align*}

Find \emph{T}(\emph{b}\textsubscript{3}) and give the matrix of \emph{T}
with respect to the standard basis of \textbf{R}\textsuperscript{2}
